+     * above this function): `u8 reserved_00[0x34]; float focus34; float
+     * focus38;` -- a classic decompiler pattern for "we don't have this
+     * struct's real field names, so address it by raw byte offset instead."
+     * Those offsets (0x34/0x38 = 52/56) are only correct against the REAL
+     * GameCube build's 32-BIT-POINTER HSF_OBJECT layout, where they land
+     * exactly on `mesh.base.scale.x`/`scale.y` (confirmed by hand: name@0
+     * type@4 constData@8 flags@12, mesh.parent@16 childNum@20 child@24
+     * base.pos@28 base.rot@40 base.scale@52 -- every member 4-byte-aligned
+     * with no gaps on a 32-bit ABI). This port's HSF_OBJECT has 8-byte
+     * pointers (name/constData/parent/child), which shifts every offset at
+     * and after `mesh.child` -- confirmed empirically via offsetof() on
+     * this exact build: mesh.child@48 (an 8-byte pointer, occupying bytes
+     * 48-55) and mesh.base.pos@56, mesh.base.scale@80. So on THIS build,
+     * raw offset 0x34(52) lands inside the upper 4 bytes of the
+     * `mesh.child` pointer (corrupting it -- harmless only because these
+     * two guide objects happen to have childNum==0, so it's never
+     * dereferenced) and offset 0x38(56) lands exactly on `mesh.base.pos.x`
+     * (NOT scale.y) -- i.e., every "focus pulse" call below was silently
